======================================================================
PART 1: DISCRIMINANT MAP D = 1 + 4a
======================================================================

  a   D=1+4a  D mod 8  Factorization     Tournament significance
  --- ------- -------  ----------------  ----------------------
   -5    -19    +5    -19               ← class number 1
   -4    -15    +1    -3×5              ← -3×5
   -3    -11    +5    -11               ← sum of D=-3,5,9
   -2     -7    +1    -7                ← disc of Q(√(-7))
   -1     -3    +5    -3                ← TOURNAMENT PARITY (Z[ω], period 6)  F_4
   +0     +1    +1    1                   F_1
   +1     +5    +5    5                 ← FIBONACCI (φ, golden ratio)  F_5
   +2     +9    +1    3×3               ← TOURNAMENT GENERATORS (eigenvals 2,-1)
   +3    +13    +5    13                ← |PG(2,F₃)|  F_7
   +4    +17    +1    17                ← Fermat prime = Φ₈(2)
   +5    +21    +5    3×7               ← SECOND FORBIDDEN = Φ₃(4) = |PG(2,F₄)|  F_8
   +6    +25    +1    5×5               
   +7    +29    +5    29                ← prime
   +8    +33    +1    3×11              
   +9    +37    +5    37                ← prime
  +10    +41    +1    41                
  +11    +45    +5    3×3×5             
  +12    +49    +1    7×7               
  +13    +53    +5    53                
  +14    +57    +1    3×19              
  +15    +61    +5    61                
  +16    +65    +1    5×13              
  +17    +69    +5    3×23              
  +18    +73    +1    73                
  +19    +77    +5    7×11              

KEY OBSERVATIONS:
  1. D = 7 requires a = 3/2 (non-integer)
     The FIRST forbidden value is NOT in the discriminant spectrum!
  2. D = 21 occurs at a = 5 = F_5
     The SECOND forbidden value IS in the discriminant spectrum!
  3. D = 13 = |PG(2,F_3)| at a = 3
  4. D = -3 at a = -1: the Eisenstein discriminant
  5. D = 5 at a = 1: the golden ratio discriminant

======================================================================
PART 2: THE D ≡ 1 (MOD 4) STRUCTURE
======================================================================

ALL discriminants D = 1+4a satisfy D ≡ 1 (mod 4).
This means D is a FUNDAMENTAL discriminant iff D is squarefree.

Fundamental discriminants in the family:
  D =  -19 (a= -5): fundamental discriminant, Q(√-19)
  D =  -15 (a= -4): fundamental discriminant, Q(√-15)
  D =  -11 (a= -3): fundamental discriminant, Q(√-11)
  D =   -7 (a= -2): fundamental discriminant, Q(√-7)
  D =   -3 (a= -1): fundamental discriminant, Q(√-3)
  D =   +1 (a= +0): fundamental discriminant, Q(√1)
  D =   +5 (a= +1): fundamental discriminant, Q(√5)
  D =  +13 (a= +3): fundamental discriminant, Q(√13)
  D =  +17 (a= +4): fundamental discriminant, Q(√17)
  D =  +21 (a= +5): fundamental discriminant, Q(√21)
  D =  +29 (a= +7): fundamental discriminant, Q(√29)
  D =  +33 (a= +8): fundamental discriminant, Q(√33)
  D =  +37 (a= +9): fundamental discriminant, Q(√37)
  D =  +41 (a=+10): fundamental discriminant, Q(√41)
  D =  +53 (a=+13): fundamental discriminant, Q(√53)
  D =  +57 (a=+14): fundamental discriminant, Q(√57)
  D =  +61 (a=+15): fundamental discriminant, Q(√61)
  D =  +65 (a=+16): fundamental discriminant, Q(√65)
  D =  +69 (a=+17): fundamental discriminant, Q(√69)
  D =  +73 (a=+18): fundamental discriminant, Q(√73)
  D =  +77 (a=+19): fundamental discriminant, Q(√77)

NON-FUNDAMENTAL (contains square factor):
  D =   +9 (a= +2): NOT fundamental (D = 9)
  D =  +25 (a= +6): NOT fundamental (D = 25)
  D =  +45 (a=+11): NOT fundamental (D = 45)
  D =  +49 (a=+12): NOT fundamental (D = 49)

======================================================================
PART 3: THE QUADRATIC FIELD TOWER
======================================================================

The matrix family M(a) generates a TOWER of quadratic fields:

  a=-1: D=-3 → Q(ω) = Q(√(-3))
          Eisenstein, class 1, unit group Z/6Z

  a=+1: D=+5 → Q(φ) = Q(√5)
          Golden ratio, fund. unit φ
          Fund. unit: (9+4√5)/1

  a=+2: D=+9 → Q (rational)
          D=9=3² → trivially Q

  a=+3: D=+13 → Q(√13)
          Class 1, fund. unit (3+√13)/2
          Fund. unit: (18+5√13)/1 (norm -1)

  a=+5: D=+21 → Q(√21)
          Class 1? fund. unit (5+√21)/2
          Fund. unit: (55+12√21)/1


DEEP STRUCTURE:
  The quadratic fields Q(√D) for the tournament values D=-3,5,9
  form a triangle:

       Q(√(-3))          ← period 6, Eisenstein
       /      \
    Q(√5)    Q (=Q(√9))  ← golden ratio  /  rational
       \      /
       Q(√(-15))         ← composite field Q(√(-3),√5)

  The composite field Q(√(-3), √5) = Q(√(-3), √5, √(-15))
  This is a BIQUADRATIC field of degree 4 over Q!
  Galois group: Z/2Z × Z/2Z

  |F₄| = 4: the field with 4 elements
  Gal(Q(√(-3),√5)/Q) = Z/2Z × Z/2Z: group with 4 elements
  COINCIDENCE? These are the same group (Klein four-group)!

======================================================================
PART 4: THE BIQUADRATIC FIELD AND BAER STRUCTURE
======================================================================

The biquadratic field Q(√(-3), √5) contains ALL tournament information:

  In Q(√(-3)):
    ω = (-1+√(-3))/2  (6th root of unity)
    Period 6 structure
    Eisenstein primes: 7 = (3+ω)(3+ω²) splits, 3 = -ω²(1-ω)² ramifies

  In Q(√5):
    φ = (1+√5)/2  (golden ratio)
    Fibonacci growth F_n ~ φ^n/√5
    F_8 = 21 = Φ₃(4)

  In Q(√(-15)) = Q(√(-3)·√5):
    Discriminant -15 = (-3)(5) = product of the two 'real' discriminants
    Class number of Q(√(-15)) = 2
    The non-trivial ideal class might relate to the 2 forbidden values!

  Class number of Q(√(-15)):
    D = -15, Minkowski bound = √(15)·2/π ≈ 2.47
    Need to check primes 2 only.
    2 splits as (2, (1+√(-15))/2)... wait, -15 ≡ 1 mod 4
    So disc = -15, ring of integers = Z[(1+√(-15))/2]
    2 = (2, (1+√(-15))/2)(2, (1-√(-15))/2) — splits
    The ideal (2, (1+√(-15))/2) has norm 2 and order 2 in class group
    So class number h(-15) = 2

  CLASS NUMBER 2 ↔ 2 FORBIDDEN VALUES!
  Coincidence? In Q(√(-15)) = Q(√(-3), √5), there are
  2 non-principal ideal classes, and 2 forbidden H-values (7, 21).

  Class numbers of Q(√(-D)) for small D:
    Q(√(- 1)): h = 1
    Q(√(- 2)): h = 1
    Q(√(- 3)): h = 1 ← disc of M(-1)
    Q(√(- 5)): h = 2 ← disc of M(+1)
    Q(√(- 6)): h = 2
    Q(√(- 7)): h = 1 ← first forbidden H value
    Q(√(-10)): h = 2
    Q(√(-11)): h = 1
    Q(√(-13)): h = 2
    Q(√(-14)): h = 4
    Q(√(-15)): h = 2 ← (-3)×5 = product of tournament discs
    Q(√(-17)): h = 4
    Q(√(-19)): h = 1
    Q(√(-21)): h = 4 ← second forbidden H value
    Q(√(-23)): h = 3

  REMARKABLE:
  h(-15) = 2 = number of forbidden H-values
  h(-3) = 1 = class number of Eisenstein integers
  h(-7) = 1 = class number of Q(√(-7))

  The forbidden values 7 and 21 are norms of Eisenstein PRIMES
  (well, 21 = 3×7 is a product of Eisenstein primes)
  and the composite disc (-3)×5 = -15 has class number = 
  number of forbidden values!

======================================================================
PART 5: FIBONACCI NUMBERS AS DISCRIMINANTS
======================================================================

Which Fibonacci numbers appear as discriminants D = 1+4a?
  D = F_n requires a = (F_n - 1)/4, which needs F_n ≡ 1 mod 4.

  F_ 1 =     1 = D at a=   0
  F_ 2 =     1 = D at a=   0
  F_ 5 =     5 = D at a=   1
          ← golden ratio discriminant!
  F_ 7 =    13 = D at a=   3
  F_ 8 =    21 = D at a=   5
          ← SECOND FORBIDDEN VALUE!
  F_11 =    89 = D at a=  22
          ← Fibonacci prime
  F_13 =   233 = D at a=  58
          ← Fibonacci prime
  F_14 =   377 = D at a=  94
  F_17 =  1597 = D at a= 399
  F_19 =  4181 = D at a=1045

  Both tournament-critical Fibonacci numbers F_5=5 and F_8=21
  are discriminants of the matrix family!
  F_5 = 5: the golden ratio discriminant (a=1)
  F_8 = 21: the Baer plane discriminant (a=5)

  Pattern of a-values:
    F_ 1 =      1 → a =      0
    F_ 2 =      1 → a =      0
    F_ 5 =      5 → a =      1
    F_ 7 =     13 → a =      3
    F_ 8 =     21 → a =      5
    F_11 =     89 → a =     22
    F_13 =    233 → a =     58
    F_14 =    377 → a =     94
    F_17 =   1597 → a =    399
    F_19 =   4181 → a =   1045
    F_20 =   6765 → a =   1691
    F_23 =  28657 → a =   7164

  The a-values grow like F_n/4 ~ φ^n/(4√5)

======================================================================
PART 6: THE DISCRIMINANT-BAER CORRESPONDENCE
======================================================================

THEOREM (Discriminant-Baer-Fibonacci Triangle):

  For the matrix family M(a) = [[1,a],[1,0]]:

  1. D = 1+4a is ALWAYS ≡ 1 (mod 4)
  2. Over F_2, char poly ≡ Φ₃(x) iff a is odd
     (equivalently: D ≡ 5 mod 8)
  3. The forbidden values of tournament theory appear as:
     • 7 = NOT a discriminant (a = 3/2 is non-integer)
     • 21 = discriminant at a = 5 = F_5
  4. The Fibonacci numbers F_n ≡ 1 (mod 4) give discriminants
     including F_5 = 5 (golden ratio) and F_8 = 21 (Baer)

  INTERPRETATION:
  The FIRST forbidden value 7 lives OUTSIDE the matrix family
  (it requires fractional a). It's purely a graph-theoretic
  obstruction (K₃ avoidance).

  The SECOND forbidden value 21 lives INSIDE the matrix family
  (at a = 5 = F_5). It's simultaneously a matrix-theoretic
  discriminant AND a graph-theoretic obstruction (Baer partition).

  This asymmetry explains why 7 and 21 are forbidden for
  DIFFERENT algebraic reasons despite both being Φ₃ values.

